05419nam a22006375i 9780822396604DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19981998ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223966047 a10.1515/97808223966042doi  a(DE-B1597)552163  a(OCoLC)893680951  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0150002bisacsh04a942.05/500aDissing Elizabeth :bNegative Representations of Gloriana /cJulia M. Walker. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1998] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b7  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Dark Side of the Cult of Elizabeth -- tHistory and Policy -- tThe Bad Seed: Princess Elizabeth and the Seymour Incident -- tWhy Did Elizabeth Not Marry? -- tThe Royal Image in Elizabethan Ireland -- t"We shall never have a merry world while the Queene lyveth": Gender, Monarchy, and the Power of Seditious Words -- tPamphlets and Sermons -- t"Souereaigne Lord of lordly Lady of this land": Elizabeth, Stubbs, and the Gaping Gvlf -- tOut of Egypt: Richard Fletcher's Sermon before Elizabeth I after the Execution of Mary Queen of Scots -- tThe Power of the Poets -- t"The Image of this Queene so quaynt": The Pornographic Blazon 1588-1603 -- tQueen Elizabeth Compiled: Henry Stanford's Private Anthology and the Question of Accountability -- t"Not as women wonted be": Spenser's Amazon Queen -- tThe Image of the Queen -- tFair Is Fowle: Interpreting Anti-Elizabethan Composite Portraiture -- tBones of Contention: Posthumous Images of Elizabeth and Stuart Politics -- tSecondary Works Cited -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDissing Elizabeth focuses on the criticism that cast a shadow on the otherwise celebrated reign of Elizabeth I. The essays in this politically and historically revealing book demonstrate the sheer pervasiveness and range of rhetoric against the queen, illuminating the provocative discourse of disrespect and dissent that existed over an eighty-year period, from her troubled days as a princess to the decades after her death in 1603.As editor Julia M. Walker suggests, the breadth of dissent considered in this collection points to a dark side of the Cult of Elizabeth. Reevaluating neglected texts that had not previously been perceived as critical of the queen or worthy of critical appraisal, contributors consider dissent in a variety of forms, including artwork representing (and mocking) the queen, erotic and pornographic metaphors for Elizabeth in the popular press, sermons subtly critiquing her actions, and even the hostility encoded in her epitaph and in the placement of her tomb. Other chapters discuss gossip about Elizabeth, effigies of the queen, polemics against her marriage to the Duke of Alençon, common verbal slander, violence against emblems of her authority, and the criticism embedded in the riddles, satires, and literature of the period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh1 aLevin, Carole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHighley, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBetts, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Ilona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalker, Julia M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorth, Marcy L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVilleponteaux, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCullough, Peter E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc